Heavy snow will move through the region overnight, easing early Tuesday morning. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, continues. A vigorous frontal system continues to give heavy rain to the region. Approximately 50 to 80 mm of rain has already fallen across North Coast inland sections near Stewart and Kitimat since last night. Further rainfall amounts of 20 to 40 mm rainfall is expected today, The front will move south of the region this evening and the rain will taper to showers. A further 20 to 30 mm is expected on Tuesday across Kitimat as another system passes through the region. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A prolonged period of snow, ice pellets, and freezing rain is expected today. The heaviest snow is expected to fall near the Alberta-N.W.T. border, with total accumulations of 10-15 cm possible. A persistent band of freezing rain and ice pellets is expected to form south of the snow. Freezing rain amounts will be highly variable, but could range from 1-5 mm. The system will exit the region later today. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Total snowfall: 10 to as much as 30 cm. Maximum wind gusts: north to northwesterly up to 110 km/h. Locations: Postville - Makkovik and Hopedale and vicinity. Time span: tonight into Tuesday morning. Remarks: Rain mixed with snow will change to snow at times heavy this evening. The transition to snow will occur in Makkovik later in the evening with snowfall accumulations near 10 cm. Higher accumulations can be expected in Hopedale and Postville. Strong northerly winds will develop with gusts up to 110 km/h overnight resulting in blowing snow. Conditions will improve Tuesday morning. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow.
